I would use two streams or rewrite it as a loop.

However, if you really want to use a (and one) stream, here is what you could do (but **not recommended**, in my opinion **streams should not have side effects**).
```java
var count = new AtomicInteger(0);

var filteredClasses = myClasses.stream()
    .peek(clazz-&gt; {
        if (!clazz.isX() &amp;&amp; clazz.isZ()) {
            count.incrementAndGet();
        }
    })
    .filter(clazz -&gt; class.isX() &amp;&amp; clazz.isY())
    .toList();
```
But this would probably take longer to execute and has more compelexity than the solution you already have.

&gt; Is it possible to do it inside one stream without having to loop though my list twice?

Yes, use the for-cycle where you perform all the operations required at once. Then you will not need to loop through the list twice or more...

```java
myClasses.forEach(myClass -&gt; {
	if (myClass.isX()) {
		if (myClass.isY()) {
			filteredClasses.add(myClass);   // x &amp;&amp; y
		}
	} else {
		if (myClass.isZ()) {
			isNotXandZCounter++;            // !x &amp;&amp; z
		}
	}
});
```

____

By the way, none of your lambda expressions are compilable.

Wrong:
- `MyClass::isX() &amp;&amp; MyClass::isY()`
- `!MyClass::isX() &amp;&amp; MyClass::isZ()`

Correct:
- `myClass -&gt; myClass.isX() &amp;&amp; myClass.isY()`
- `myClass -&gt; !myClass.isX() &amp;&amp; myClass.isZ()`

And collecting into a list is done via `.collect(Collectors.toList())` and not `.Collectors.toList()`.

